I think Jay-Z got some inspiration for this video from Imi Kamoze's "Here Comes the Hotstepper.". From the black and white color, to the stand-alone rapping with dark shades on by himself, as opposed to being surrounded by a bunch of dancers, to mention of several famous names (DeNiro, Sinatra, LeBron, Dwayne Wade).  Hotstepper didn't mention names but actually showed a lot of famous faces in the video (Sophia Loren, Julia Roberts and top models of that era).  Also, the famous landmarks in Paris shown in Hotstepper, while Empire State also mentioned or showed famous landmarks.  Just my observation.  Hotstepper was such a gigantic success, it's easy to understand that it would be an inspiration for other artists.  Just an observation.  Both Hotstepper and Empire State are equally timeless classics nonetheless.  I love both, never get tired of those beats.

I would like to point out that American - English is not my native language. This song for me has a very particular and funny story at the same time. It was the summer of 2011 and my friends and I used to spend all the days on the beach together, we were around 13-14 years old. I remember this song playing on the bar radio and it immediately stuck in my head. I started singing it in my own way, changing lots of words, at the time I wasn't at all familiar with English. There was this friend of mine who was very good at English so I asked her: "Hey, what's the name of that song that goes "Enduioooo"?" She started laughing but she didn't really know the song in question. A few years later I listened to it again by chance and using Shazam I found the title. The first thing I did was write to my friend, reminding her of that question I asked her years before. My "Enduiooo" was actually "New Yoooork". Every summer we see each other, we think about this story and laugh about it. Obviously for me the refrain will always be "Enduioooo".
